The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, May 15, 2004 				 Novartis profit jumps 84%
																								May 14 (PTI): Novartis India Ltd has reported an 83.48 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 113.76 crore for the fiscal ended March 31, 2004, compared with Rs 62 crore posted in previous fiscal. Net sales increased to Rs 504.94 crore from Rs 471.7 crore a year ago. The board has recommended a dividend of 200 per cent for 2003-04, a company said.																								For the fourth quarter ended March, net profit jumped to Rs 20.87 crore (Rs 1.32 crore) on net sales of Rs 102.34 crore (Rs 76.76 crore).																								Pharmaceutical business was the key contributor to profits. Pharmaceutical sales for the period closed at Rs 310 crore, registering a growth of 6.2 per cent.																								Novartis said the generics business registered a loss of Rs 40 lakh despite 9.8 per cent rise in sales at Rs 109 crore.Tata Telecom net up																								Tata telecom today posted a 76 per cent growth in profit after tax at Rs 32.76 crore for the year ended March 31, 2004. Turnover was up 23 per cent at Rs 401.93 crore,the company said in a statement. The board recommended a dividend of 45 per cent for the fiscal 2003-04.																								For the fourth quarter, net profit increased 27 per cent to Rs 10.55 crore and revenue was up 20 per cent to Rs 132.50 crore.Kanoria Chemicals																								Kanoria Chemicals amp; Industries Ltd reported 55.7 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 19.8 crore in 2003-04 and announced a 25 per cent dividend. The company would give 13.5 per cent dividend on cumulative redeemable preference shares for the last fiscal.																								Sales were up by 7 per cent to Rs 360.30 crore last fiscal, the company said in a release.Welspun posts profit 																								Welspun India registered a 34 per cent rise in net profit to Rs 34.02 crore for 2003-04. Total income increased to Rs 374.49 crore. 																								The company has announced Rs 499 crore worth expansion plans, which include setting up of a spinning mill.
